      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, let's refine the sorting function to explicitly handle the sorting logic. I'll write a custom sort function using the insertion sort algorithm, which guarantees a O(n^2) time complexity in the worst case, but may perform well on nearly sorted data. However, for very large datasets you might want to consider alternative, more efficient sorting algorithms like merge sort or quick sort. For now, we'll use insertion sort as it's straightforward and deterministic.\n\n```python\ndef custom_sort(arr):\n    # A simple, deterministic insertion sort implementation\n    for i in range(1, len(arr)):\n        key = arr[i]\n        j = i - 1\n\n        # Move elements of arr[0..i-1], that are greater than key, to one position ahead\n        while j >= 0 and key < arr[j]:\n            arr[j + 1] = arr[j]\n            j -= 1\n        arr[j + 1] = key\n\n    return arr\n\n# Test cases\ndef test_cases():\n    assert custom_sort([10, 5, 8, 2]) == [2, 5, 8, 10]\n    assert custom_sort([1, 1, 1]) == [1",
